Central Park: A set of 5 views of the Arsenal under reconstruction as viewed westward (north and southward) from Fifth Ave. (foreground) at East 64th Street. This structure was erected in 1848 at a cost of $30,000 (as given in 1853). The City of New York purchased same in 1856 from the State for a sum of $275,000. The first floor was used for Administrative offices while the 2nd and 3rd were occupied by the Museum, which later became the American Museum of Natural History. The Meteorological Observatory for years occupied a large upper room.

January 1924.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Fifth Avenue at N. E. corner of 65th Street; residence of John Jacob Astor (lost in "Titanic" disaster), now demolished.
June, 1925.

Fifth Avenue at N.E. corner of 65th Street, showing John Jacob Astor residence.
Demolished to make way for new Temple Emanu-El. 1926.
Wurts Brothers, Photographers.

Fifth Avenue, at the N.E. corner of East 65th Street, showing at that location the Temple Emanu-El, erected here in 1927 on the former site of the John Jacob Astor mansion. The photographer is viewing same from the 65th Street lateral high-way thru Central Park.

This organization was formerly located at the N.E. corner of Fifth Avenue and East 43rd Street in a synagogue erected in 1868. Their earlier meetings were held in the Grand Street Court-room (1845 to 1850). Subsequently they purchased a former church on Chrystie Street and remodelled same for their purpose (1850 to 1856). A Baptist church building on East 12th Street preceded the first - Fifth Avenue structure (1856 to 1868).

View 1: May 21, 1933
View 2: April 23, 1938

P. L. Sperr
